reviewText: Full of surprises!  Fascinating discussion around bisexuality and cross-dressing.  Without getting into spoilers - was shocked and impressed at Gabriel's choice in relationships.
Not worth the money.  All interview and no action.  Expected a little more skin.
It was okay. I don't want to be rude to the people in the show so I'll just leave it at that.
It's a job that requires a lot of upkeep, and it can't be an easy way to make a living. It reminded me of a Pointer Sisters hit, "She Works Hard for the Money."
This was not a movie. It was a badly made low budget autobiography that stopped at the end with the narrator in the middle of a sentence.

Interesting, but not enough to watch this again.  I was intrigued by the guy who had the "big" girl as a girl friend, but was also into this guy friend of his (girl friend was aware of it).  I guess that's one of my "misconceptions"  that most male strippers are gay, which is probably not true. As I stated at the start, it interesting to hear these guys talk honestly about themselves.

This was actually a  major disappointment. When you see Bronco from the rear  going on stage his butt crack is blurred. I would think that this being a movie about strippers that you would not think that this would be censored. After awhile you do not care that Gabriel is bisexual, this is obviously a major issue in this movie and after a short period of time in this movie and in real life, who really cares anymore. Also, when he is in bed with his girl friend he is wearing underwear, this was the most least erotic, sensual movie about male strippers I have ever seen. I did not throw this in the trash yet but it is definitely headed that way. You see more in "Magic Mike" than you will ever see here. One star is really too generous.
